":"1302","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1320":"1320","1339":"1339","Hambye, Manche, Normandie, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk","La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandy, France":"La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1270–":"1270–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1272–Female":"1272–Deceased","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1295–1339":"1295–1339","1302–1350":"1302–1350","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1250–1295":"1250–1295","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","environ 1320":"about 1320","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","Abt 1295":"about 1295","1302":"1302","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1320":"1320","1339":"1339","Hambye, Manche, Normandie, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France","La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandy, France":"La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandy, France","France":"France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"PAYNEL","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de PAYNEL Baron de Hambye , seigneur de Fumechon, Bréhal et Bricqueville was born in 1270, in La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandy, France, his father, Foulques IV de PAYNEL seigneur de Fumechon, Bréhal et Bricqueville, was 21 and his mother, Jeanne de BIGARS Heiress de Furnechon, was 25. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Marguerite d'AVAUGOUR. He died in Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1272–